Introduction¶

This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

  • ScheduledDay: tells us on what day the patient set up their appointment.
  • Neighborhood: indicates the location of the hospital.
  • Scholarship: indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia.
  • 'No-show': 'No' if the patient showed up to their appointment, and 'Yes' if they did show up

Questions¶

This report investigates the factors are may affect if the patient will show up for their scheduled appointment?

Mainly this report will tackle the following questions

  • Does gender affect if the patient will show up for scheduled appointment?
  • Does patients who wait less for their appointments show up to their appointments more?
  • Does age affect if the patient will show up for scheduled appointment?
  • Does being handicapped affect if the patient will show up for scheduled appointment?
  • what about other factors such as (scholarship, hypertension, diabetes, alcoholic, reminder SMS)

def get_percentage (df, column):
    """
    It takes a dataframe and a column name as input, and returns the percentage of patients who showed up for their appointment, grouped by the column specified.
    
    :param df: the dataframe
    :param column: the column you want to get the percentage of
    :return: The percentage of patients who showed up for their appointment, grouped by the column specified.

    for example if column is "scholarship":
    
        no_show             scholarship
        0 (did show up)       0              80.192844
                              1              76.263696
        1 (didn't show up)    0              19.807156
                              1              23.736304

    """
    count = df.groupby(['no_show', column]).count()['patientid']
    totals = df.groupby(column).count()['patientid']
    fraction = count/totals
    return fraction*100

Data Cleaning¶

In [9]:
# get rid of typos and rename columns to be lowercase and consistent
df.rename(columns= {'Hipertension': 'hypertension', 'Handcap': 'handicap'}, inplace= True)
df.rename(columns= lambda x:x.strip().casefold().replace('-', '_'), inplace= True)

# Change dates columns to appropiate date type
df[['scheduledday', 'appointmentday']] = df[['scheduledday', 'appointmentday']].apply(pd.to_datetime)

# Change values of no_show column to be 0: if the patient did showup, and 1: if the patient didn't show up
df.no_show = df['no_show'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == 'No' else 1)

Does patients who wait less for their appointments show up to their appointments more?¶

In [14]:
df['waiting_days'] = (df['appointmentday'] - df['scheduledday']).dt.days

# disable warning that occurs when I change the waiting_days of -1 to 0
pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None  # default='warn

# Change the value of waiting_days that are below zero to zero
df['waiting_days'][df.waiting_days < 0] = 0 

x = get_percentage(df, 'waiting_days')
show_wait = x.loc[0]

ind = np.arange(len(show_wait))

fig_1 = plt.figure(figsize=(10,8), dpi = 100)
axes_1 = fig_1.add_axes([0,0,1,1])

axes_1.plot(ind, show_wait,color = 'red', marker= 'o', markerfacecolor = 'blue', markeredgecolor = 'k', ls = '-.')

# Display Title, xlabel, ylabel, xticks, and xticks
axes_1.set_title('Does waiting affect showing up to appointment?', fontsize = 18, fontweight = 'bold')
axes_1.set_xlabel('Waiting days between scheduling and appointment', fontsize = 15, fontweight = 'bold')
axes_1.set_ylabel('Percentage of patients that show up %', fontsize =15, fontweight = 'bold')

plt.show()

Interesting
The percentange of patients that show up is high (>80%) when the appointment day is the same as scheduled day (No wating time)
However, the percentage of patients that show up decreases to around (65%) when the patient has to wait more than 1 day up to 85 days.
Finally, the percentage of patients that show up increases again, when the patient waits more than 85 days.

So what is the hypothesis for such an increase after the patients wait more than 85 days?
(Is it because they receive more reminder SMS in comparison to people who wait less or is it because that there are few patients that wait more than 85 days to get to appointment?)

Indeed patients who waited more than 85 days received more SMS in comparison to people who waited less than 85 days. However, patients who waited more than 85 days are very few compared to patients who waited less then 85 days.

So, The most probable reason for such an increase in percentage of patients who (show up) after the patients wait more than 85 days is due to the fact there are very patients who actually wait more than 85 days

x = get_percentage(df, 'age')

show_age = x[0]
no_show_age = x[1]

# for people aged 99, all of them showed up, so adding age 99 to the no_show series and give a value of 0%, so that len(show) == len(no_show)
no_show_age['99'] = 0

age = np.arange(len(show_age)) # indices for the bars (0 to 99) which corresponds to age
width = 1 # width of the bar chart

# Plot the Bar Chart
fig_2 = plt.figure(figsize=(10,8), dpi=100)

# Plot bar chart for age interval for people who didn't show up
plt.bar(age, no_show_age, width, color = 'r', edgecolor= 'k', label = 'No show', bottom = show_age)
plt.bar(age, show_age, width, color = 'b', edgecolor= 'k', label = 'Show up')

# Display Title, xlabel, ylabel, xticks, and a legend
plt.title('Does Age affect showing up to appointment?', fontsize = 18, fontweight = 'bold')
plt.xlabel('Years', fontsize = 15, fontweight = 'bold')
plt.ylabel('Percentage of patients %', fontsize =15, fontweight = 'bold')

Conclusion
People who are more handicapped are more likely not to show up to a doctor appointments
Kinda make sense, since those patients may require help from relative or a friend to show up to the doctor appointment

What is the effect that the patient having scholarship, hypertension, diabetes may not show up to a doctor appointment?¶

What is the effect that the patient being alcoholic or not receiving a reminder sms may not show up to the appointment?¶

In [20]:
columns = ['scholarship', 'hypertension', 'diabetes', 'alcoholism', 'sms_received'] # all these columns have either (0) or (1)

# Create empty list for people without certain attribute (e.g. scholarship, hypertension ... etc) and did SHOW UP
show_no_attr = []
# Create empty list for people with certain attribute (e.g. scholarship, hypertension ... etc) and did SHOW UP
show_attr = []

for column in columns:
    
    percentage = get_percentage(df, column)
    
    # people without certain attribute e.g.(without scholarship, hypertension ..etc) and did show
    show_no_attr.append(percentage.loc[0][0])

    # people with certain attribute e.g.(with scholarship, hypertension ..etc) and did show
    show_attr.append(percentage.loc[0][1])

ind = np.arange(len(show_no_attr))

width = 0.3

fig_3 = plt.figure(figsize=(10,8), dpi = 100)

# Plot bar char (people with certain attribute (e.g. with scholarship) showing who did show up and who didn't)
plt.bar(ind, show_attr, width = width, edgecolor='k', color= 'blue')

# Plot bar char (people without certain attribute (e.g. without scholarship) showing who did show up and who didn't)
plt.bar(ind+ width, show_no_attr, width = width, edgecolor= 'k', color= 'red')


# Function that add "No" before the string, used to generate of xticks_labels from column i.e. scholarship, no scholarship ...etc
function = lambda x:'No {}'.format(x).title()

# Generate xticks_labels from columns ['scholarship', 'No scholarship', 'hypertension', 'No hypertension' ... etc]
xticks_labels = [f(x) for x in columns for f in (lambda x:x.title(), function)]

# Calculate xticks_location for each bar
xticks_locations = np.concatenate((ind, ind + width))
xticks_locations.sort(kind='mergesort')

# plot title, x&y labels, xticks, and legend
plt.title('What is the effect of different factors to show up to a doctor appointment?', fontsize = 18, fontweight = 'bold')
plt.xlabel('Factors', fontsize = 15, fontweight = 'bold')
plt.ylabel('Percentage of patients that show up %', fontsize = 15, fontweight = 'bold')
plt.xticks(xticks_locations, xticks_labels, rotation = 90)


plt.show()

Conclusion
Patients with hypertension or diabetes show up to the doctor appointments slightly more than patients without hypertension or diabetes

Alcohol has no effect whether the patient may show up to doctor appointments or none

Interestingly patients with scholarship and patients who receive a reminder SMS show up to doctor appointments slightly less than patients without scholarship and didn't receive a reminder SMS

Limitations¶

  1. In some patients the appointment date was set before scheduled date, which resulted that waiting time value for some patients was -1 day, this was corrected by assuming that waiting time was zero days
  2. Some age values are in negative
